# Caveman commit messages

Conventional Commits. Why over what. No narrative fluff.

## Subject

- Format: `<type>(<scope>): <imperative summary>` — scope optional
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `perf`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `build`, `ci`, `style`, `revert`
- Imperative: add/fix/remove — not added/adds/adding
- Aim ≤50 chars; hard cap 72; no trailing period
- Match repo capitalization after colon

## Body

Omit when subject enough. Add for: non-obvious **why**, breaking changes, migrations, linked issues. Wrap ~72 cols; bullets use `-`. Issues at end: `Closes #42`, `Refs #17`.

## Never include

"This commit…", I/we/now/currently; AI attribution; emoji (unless repo requires); restating filename when scope covers it.

## Auto-clarity

Breaking changes, security fixes, data migrations, revert commits: **always** include body context — not subject-only.

## Output only

Emit message in a fenced block for paste. Do not run `git commit` unless user asks.

Off: **stop caveman-commit** or **normal mode** → verbose commit style.
